[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"achievement","header":"Founded Mahoning Valley Historical Society, 1874","body":"In 1874 John Miller Edwards founded the Mahoning Valley Historical Society in Youngstown, Ohio — one of the earliest county-level historical societies in the Western Reserve. He served as Youngstown correspondent for the Cleveland Herald for fourteen years from 1865 to 1879. He co-edited the 1882 History of Trumbull and Mahoning Counties published in Cleveland."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Edited first newspaper in Mahoning County, 1846","body":"Edwards published and edited the Mahoning Index in 1846 — the first newspaper in the newly-formed Mahoning County, Ohio. He had earlier edited the Trumbull Democrat through the 1840s and was later associate editor of the Mahoning Register. His thirty-year journalism career coincided with the region's rapid industrial growth around iron and steel."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"Yale 1824; admitted to Connecticut and Ohio bars","body":"Edwards graduated from Yale in 1824 and was admitted to the Connecticut bar in 1826 after reading law with Judge Bristol in New Haven. He moved to the Youngstown area in 1832 and was admitted to the Ohio bar in 1838. His later positions included commissioner of bankrupts for Trumbull County and justice of the peace for Youngstown township from 1869 to 1878."}],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","dates":"1824","notes":" — Yale class of 1824. Son of Gov. Henry Waggaman Edwards (HD2045). Founder of the Mahoning Valley Historical Society; journalist; lawyer. Settled in Youngstown Ohio area."}],"slug":"john-edwards-1805"},"HD2104":{"id":"HD2104","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"HD2102","mother_id":"X00676"},"tags":["compiler_ancestor"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1845,"month":8,"day":31,"city":"Canfield","state":"Ohio"},"death":{"year":1932,"month":2,"day":21,"city":"Denver","state":"Colorado"},"gender":"female","marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X01545","children_ids":[],"marriage_number":1}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"She knew exactly who she was","detail":"The passage reads: \"Mrs. Caspar is descended from the Rev. Solomon Stoddard, the Rev. James Pierrepont and the Rev. Thomas Hooker, who in 1636 led his band of adherents out of Newton (Cambridge) and founded the Hartford settlement.\" This is among the most complete contemporary acknowledgments by a living descendant of the full Hooker genealogical chain. She and her husband came to Denver in 1887 from Youngstown Ohio; she died in 1932 age 86, having led civic organizations in Montana, Ohio, and Colorado for six decades. (History of Colorado Vol. 5, 1927)","body":"Her 1927 Colorado biographical entry documents the full genealogical chain: Thomas Hooker, Rev. James Pierpont, Rev. Solomon Stoddard, and Jonathan Edwards — all named as her direct ancestors.","number":1},{"number":2,"category":"social_reform","header":"Denver’s serial founder of clubs","body":"She founded the Colorado Colonial Dames, the Monday Literary Club, the Homer Club of Montana, and the Twenty-second Avenue Study Club — presiding over the last for thirty years — and led Colorado’s state board of charities. Her $72,000 estate went to the cathedral, the hospital, the YWCA, and the Old Ladies Home of her native Youngstown."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Henrietta Frances Edwards","first_name":"Henrietta","middle_name":"Frances","maiden_name":"Edwards","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[